# Output Template

Use this shape when answering workflow-finder requests.

## Short Answer

Start with the strongest answer in one or two sentences:

```text
Closest match: [repo]. It is closest because [reason].
For your workflow, treat it as [fit label], not [wrong role].
```

## Repo Table

Return 3-7 matches unless the user asks for a longer list.

| Repo | Fit | Workflow type it teaches | Why it matches |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| `[owner/repo](url)` | Codex-native / skill-package / inspiration / runtime / source taxonomy | EvidenceAudit, DocumentTransformation, CaseIntake, etc. | One concrete similarity |

## Codex/ECC Read

Include a brief recommendation:

```text
For Codex config packages, use [repo] as [role]. Keep ECC as the workflow
contract. Do not make [platform/runtime] the source of truth unless you want that
execution environment.
```

## Search Terms Used Or Suggested

When useful, include 3-6 search phrases:

```text
public evidence audit agent skill
real estate due diligence agent skill
healthcare referral packet agent workflow
```

## Next Step

End with a concrete next move:

- inspect the top repo;
- clone/read a specific folder;
- build a local `workflow-pattern-router`;
- refresh stars/current state;
- create a new Codex workflow pack from the matched pattern.

Keep tone concise. The user prefers direct repo recommendations over broad
explanations.


